Zensho Holdings (7550) | Japan
Announces Price Cofor Regular Gyudon from ￥480 to ￥450

On Aug 28, the company announced a price cut for its regular- sized gyudon from ￥480 to ￥450- This move could serve as a catalyst to reverse the decline in customer traffic following the foreign object incident- Although a price cut, margins may improve via increased sales from higher customer traffic

Sukiya's same- store customer traffic has continued to trend down YoY since the contamination incident in Mar this year. This price cut from ￥480 to ￥450 for regular gyudon may help reverse the downtrend in customer traffic. In the gyudon industry, a stiff price competition among the three majors occurred post- 2009, eroding profitability in overall industry. Compared to that period when the yen was stronger, a similar scenario is unlikely this time. While the price cut may reduce gross margin, it may be possible for the company to improve OPM with increased sales from higher customer traffic via operating leverage. Thus, we see no need to be overly negative on the price cut.
Zensho Holdings (7550, T, 7550 JP)

Our PT of ¥11,400 is based on our F3/26 EPS estimate of ¥307.7 and a P/E of 37x, a 15% premium to the average P/E of 32x for 16 food service companies with market caps of at least ¥100bn. 15% is the average premium at which Zensho traded vs. the industry average in F3/23. We assign a premium as the company is performing better than peers both in Japan and abroad.
- Fall in rice prices- Further rise in same-store sales for Sukiya and Hamasushi- Further overseas growth driven by faster store openings and M&As outside Japan.
- Failure to pass along higher ingredient costs or rising labor expenses- Worsening same-store sales for Sukiya and Hamasushi- Growth slowdown due to decline in same-store sales overseas
